1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Good.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Okay.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Today is Wednesday June 1, 2011.

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:25,000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:32,000
I'm with filmmaker and biographer John Bishop. We are in Montgomery, Alabama to do an oral history interview

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:44,000
for the series for the project entitled The Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

8
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Today we're in Montgomery to visit with Dr. Gwendolyn M. Patton. Dr. Patton, thank you so much for the welcome and it's a pleasure to be here.

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Thank you.

10
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,000
I thought I'd start today.

11
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Before we turn down, we talked about the fact that there are places here in your longer story where we want to be sure we place some extra emphasis.

12
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Let me pick up today with this question for us to begin.

13
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Can you paint the picture of Tuskegee in the fall of 61 when you arrived to start your years at Tuskegee?

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Well, it was impressive. It was a large campus in terms of acreage.

15
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:36,000
The buildings were very, to some extent, ornate.

16
00:01:36,000 --> 00:02:00,000
The main street leading up to the university, which we called Campus Avenue, intrigued me because there were no front entrances to the buildings on the main thoroughfare.

17
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
So I was intrigued by that.

18
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:11,000
And then of course, when we went through the Lincoln Gate, I knew that was named after Abraham Lincoln.

19
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,000
The National Guard greeted us.

20
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:25,000
And that somewhat didn't frighten me, but it bothered me.

21
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And they were very courteous, but courteous.

22
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And living with my grandmother, my called mommy, on my mother's side, I knew how to be stoic and not to be too expressive.

23
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And I took cues from her and we went right onto the campus.

24
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Later I learned that the National Guard had been called up because they were integrating the schools in the city.

25
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:16,000
And they were to be there for protection, which kind of baffled me because they were state troopers.

26
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
And they had never been friendly or kind.

27
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And I had some understanding how the state could be trumped, if you will, by the federal, by the national.

28
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:44,000
And so they were not under the auspices of I think Governor John Patterson at the time, but rather under President Kennedy at the time.

29
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,000
So I learned that and I worked through that.

30
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:59,000
And the buildings with no doors on the main thoroughfare, which you would assume, I later learned,

31
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:16,000
that Book of T. Washington, even though I have to make clear that Adams found it the school, but Book of T. Washington developed the school.

32
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And though he was called an uncle Tom, especially by the black intelligence here, with his the five fingers of the hand and all of that, the Atlanta exposition and an argument with W.E.B. Du Bois,

33
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:49,000
that I learned that indeed he was a race man. And he built the doors front doors, entrances, facing the campus.

34
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And because the thoroughfare was used by white and black people, and he didn't want them to feel like they were welcomed.

35
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And so all of the doors, if you go there even to this day, they're faced inward to the campus.

36
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:16,000
So that kind of pleased me, I like that. And then I learned a lot more about Tuskegee's history from subsequent presidents, much later in life.

37
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:30,000
But when I broke my leg in the car, I didn't break it, but this mysterious car accident in 1967, I had learned a lot about Tuskegee, its history.

38
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:53,000
I knew some before I went there, because when I was 12 years old or 11, I wrote my paper on George Washington Carver, and tried to dispel the myth of the peanut man, you know, that kind of reduced him.

39
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:12,000
And I saw him as a scientist, and I learned about Yams (sweet potatoes) and peanuts, because he also did stuff with Yams (sweet potatoes) and peanuts, and I learned about paints, and I also understood he had contracts with the paint people, and I learned about Ford, Henry Ford.

40
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:26,000
I think my daddy told me that my father, Clarence Robert Patton Sr, was a race man. In fact, I come from a race family on both sides.

41
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:54,000
So I was rather astute in the history of black people, even as a child. And so in 1967, with all of that thinking, all of what I knew about Tuskegee, Robert Russa Moton, who was the president of Tuskegee, after Washington, and they were building the VA hospital,

42
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:22,000
mainly for World War I veterans. I mean, not mainly, but for black, World War I veterans, there was this dispute, as to who would be the doctors, and the nurses, the professional staff, and the authorities to be coming from Washington, we have to understand Woodrow Wilson.

43
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:37,000
He said that the professional staff will be white people, and the help, the maintenance, and the nurses' aids, and the bedpan deliverers, and removers, and all of that, will be black people.

44
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:59,000
Well, Robert Russa Moton, who was president, said, no, we have black doctors. In fact, Tuskegee had a nursing program for RNs, or to become RNs, and there was Meharry Medical College, which produced black doctors.

45
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:11,000
And he said, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, we're going to have black professional staff, and living within the confines of Jim Crow, he was kind of on target.

46
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:24,000
And the white powers to be, because they saw money, they saw jobs, said, that's not going to be. So it became a big struggle. We're talking about in the 1920s now,

47
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:44,000
1910s, 18s, you know, teens, and they said that if a black person, professional, crossed those doors at the VA hospital, the clan will be there to do X, Y, and Z, which was violence.

48
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:58,000
And Dr. Moton said, okay, so he called out all of the World War I black veterans. This is lower, because I was not there, and nor were my parents.

49
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:12,000
And the story is that they lined the highway to the VA hospital, the black veterans, and the clan never showed up.

50
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:17,000
It's a proud history, there's no question of Tuskegee.

51
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Yeah, and so to bring that full circle in 1967, when I was in this mysterious car accident in shorter Alabama,

52
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:52,000
and I was by myself in John Andrew Memorial Hospital, which was on the campus, and coming through some recovery, and that's a whole nother story.

53
00:09:52,000 --> 00:10:05,000
I wrote a piece called Book of Teawashintern in retrospect, the father of black power, which validated why I wanted to go to Tuskegee,

54
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:21,000
in the first place. And what people don't know is that the Tuskegee Black Power Conference, and not in New Jersey.

55
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:33,000
And so Tuskegee was part of my deepening, my understanding of race pride and race progress.

56
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,000
The conference you've just mentioned is the one in 1967 organized by Sharp?

57
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
Yeah.

58
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
In Jersey? No, the one on the campus.

59
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:54,000
On campus it was organized by SNCC, and I under-wrote it. You talk about the Southern Human Relations Project, which was, and we call it, Sharp.

60
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:00,000
We under-wrote it. You have to understand my role as a sharp organizer.

61
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:01,000
We'll come to that.

62
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:02,000
Okay.

63
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
But it was really led by SNCC.

64
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:08,000
We'll come to that in some detail. That's great. We'll talk that through.

65
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:17,000
Your initial, obviously, we won't stop to do a lot of the personal history that brings you that point, but by 61, you obviously, as you say, are kind of a race person.

66
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:28,000
You're very attentive and conscious about these things. Your family's been quite assertively attentive in many different ways.

67
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:29,000
All of my life.

68
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:31,000
That's exactly what I'm talking about.

69
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:38,000
But you're also a student starting college, and you do things like cheerleading and going to class and theater or these things.

70
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:51,000
Is there much that distinguishes that period between your arrival on the campus and your departure to the sanitary when you have to go for the TV period to work your losses?

71
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:58,000
Is there much in that early period on the campus where you're closely connected to civil rights or not?

72
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:04,000
Yes, because I had to communicate back to Montgomery.

73
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:10,000
And you had the Freedom Riders that come through.

74
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:17,000
That's when I learned some additional things about my family.

75
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:19,000
This is the prior spring.

76
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:27,000
May, 1960, what I call it, the Mother's Day Massacre.

77
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:37,000
And the following day, which was a school day, if I may.

78
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:41,000
Well, I was at the mass meeting that they held all night.

79
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:46,000
Let's back up just once, so what happens is the Freedom Riders come into town.

80
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:47,000
Right.

81
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:51,000
And there's just all kinds of activity.

82
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
The Montgomery movement infrastructure jumped into our gear.

83
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:04,000
He's a great re who was a secretary to Dr. King and the Montgomery Improvement Association.

84
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:15,000
And dear mentor of mine, along with some other ladies, Mrs. Odessa, Williams later became ready.

85
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:25,000
They all jumped into gear to rescue and provide refuge for the Freedom Riders.

86
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:29,000
Telephones were above us with they beating us too out of them.

87
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:40,000
You know, do something, but not in the household where I was with my aunt chick and my aunt Flora, who were two school teachers.

88
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:49,000
My grandmother, mommy, eccentric did not have a telephone.

89
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:50,000
Okay.

90
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:52,000
And I could do it.

91
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:04,000
But my aunt Mary, who lived next door to my aunt chick, who had lived in Pittsburgh, was a little bit more broad-minded.

92
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:14,000
And so she was a part of the movement in somewhat of a real sense, though my aunt chick and aunt Flora were as well, in lending their cars.

93
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:30,000
But they were school teachers and, you know, the reprisals, as well as, they were kind of status conscious.

94
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:36,000
If you understand what I'm saying, they were school teachers, quote unquote.

95
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:48,000
Aunt Mary was a synchronous, also a school teacher, but had made a living basically as a synchronous and a tailoress.

96
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And her husband was self-employed, you know, as a house painter.

97
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:02,000
So Aunt Mary comes to tell me about what's happening downtown at the Greyhound bus station.

98
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
And I want to go to the mass meeting.

99
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:11,000
I knew Aunt Chick was not going to take me because I was a child of the entire family.

100
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:24,000
I went to Aunt Mary's house, called my grandparents, the patents, who were very much involved, and they were independent workers at the Greyhound business.

101
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,000
They came and got me.

102
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
And so I went to that and said, I don't know that.

103
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:38,000
I have to ask you to say a little more because you stay all night because of very complicated, difficult situation.

104
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,000
Can you explain that at the mass meeting?

105
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,000
Well, as a child, I'm 17.

106
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:50,000
I knew there was terror outside the clubsters, as we called them.

107
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:56,000
We didn't call them KKK. We called them clubsters, my family called them the clubsters.

108
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:07,000
But as a teenager, like other teenagers in that mass meeting, we felt invincible.

109
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:17,000
And the adults, most of whom knew that God was going to protect us.

110
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:23,000
And see, that had been introduced and then reinforced during the Montgomery bus boycott.

111
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,000
We knew there was divine intervention.

112
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:29,000
So basically there was no fear.

113
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:33,000
Now we saw all these white men walking up and down and down and up.

114
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:35,000
You know, inside, I had no idea.

115
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:38,000
They were police or detectors or whatever.

116
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:41,000
I thought there were newspaper people.

117
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And so that was that.

118
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:49,000
And then a youngster, young and then I, Jolacy,

119
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:54,000
was summing downstairs in the basement.

120
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:58,000
And you have to see first, this is a beautiful church.

121
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:08,000
And I later learned, I didn't know that night, that he was instructed to crawl through the basement window,

122
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:16,000
to go to his grandmother's home, which was not far, to make telephone calls for those who had telephones,

123
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,000
to let people know we were okay.

124
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:22,000
And he had to crawl under the houses.

125
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And at that time, we didn't have encasement around houses.

126
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:29,000
The houses were built on what I call sticks.

127
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And then later on they put a looming them around them, and then later on they break them.

128
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,000
And so forth. And later on they tore them down.

129
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:40,000
So that I do recall.

130
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
He was about 14, youngster.

131
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:47,000
I was 17, a senior in the old 90s.

132
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:50,000
I recall that.

133
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:54,000
But we're just saying songs.

134
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:56,000
And you know.

135
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:04,000
I think that day, earlier that day, some of the Freedom Riders have come to one of your relatives home.

136
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,000
My aunt Chick's home.

137
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:08,000
And an integrated group of writers.

138
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:09,000
Right.

139
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,000
And I'm interested in having you account the reaction of your...

140
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:16,000
Oh my goodness.

141
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:18,000
So I had them over.

142
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,000
I was curious.

143
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,000
I'd been up all night with them, you know.

144
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:23,000
And see there were lots of them.

145
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:26,000
So this is the day following, the day following.

146
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:35,000
And some of them stayed out at Reb and Solomon's Saves home, out in Madison Park.

147
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:38,000
And that's another story.

148
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:40,000
It's an old black community.

149
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:49,000
So anyway, teenagers all over the city, I don't want to make it seem like it was just me,

150
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:56,000
that sections of Freedom Riders came to each other's homes.

151
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:00,000
And my home was selected where I lived.

152
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
And I was staying with my aunt Chick and Flora, who were school teachers.

153
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:14,000
And I was enjoying them talking about the freedom movement and all of that.

154
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:20,000
And when aunt Chick came home, Flora taught in Lowndes County, which is the country.

155
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:24,000
So she came home much later along with a drive.

156
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:29,000
And aunt Chick was very smart in her dress.

157
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:34,000
You know, you know, and she wore these spike high heels.

158
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:37,000
And she had a clickety-clack when she walked.

159
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:40,000
I mean, poise and all of that business.

160
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:49,000
And when she came home and walked through the living room and saw these black and white kids

161
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:58,000
or young adults sitting on our sofa, I did not notice that she was disconcerted.

162
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,000
She didn't just display that.

163
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:09,000
And because of whatever affectations, and maybe I even have some of that as being a product of that,

164
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:14,000
she says, Gwendolyn come with me and I go to the kitchen.

165
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:16,000
And I knew she was going to get cookies and lemonade.

166
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:18,000
I mean, that's the nice thing to do.

167
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:21,000
We call them repass.

168
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:29,000
And as we prepare the tray, aunt Chick said to me in a very...

169
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:35,000
...and monitoring tone.

170
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:40,000
I don't want any white people in my house.

171
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:43,000
Now, I'm a race person.

172
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:49,000
And I see many white people in my life, my entire life.

173
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,000
But I saw something a little different about.

174
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:54,000
It was only one white boy.

175
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And I saw something different about him.

176
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:03,000
And I said, oh, aunt Chick, I say, I might have used...

177
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,000
They're different kinds of white people.

178
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:07,000
They're not like the clubsters.

179
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,000
You know, I have this discussion.

180
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:12,000
And she made it very clear.

181
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:17,000
As long as I have to go through the back door of white folks houses,

182
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:21,000
they're not to enter the front door of my home.

183
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:26,000
And we always made a distinction between houses and home.

184
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:29,000
And I had to take that under consideration.

185
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:32,000
And then we... she clicked like...

186
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:36,000
...and I'm following behind her, took the lemonade and the cookies...

187
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:38,000
...out to the group.

188
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:42,000
And we ate and they stayed a little while and then they soon left.

189
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:52,000
Let me ask you about your experience in the sanitarium in Lafayette, Alabama.

190
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:54,000
Lafayette, Alabama.

191
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:55,000
Lafayette, Alabama, excuse me.

192
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:57,000
Lafayette, Alabama.

193
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:00,000
Lafayette, Alabama, Alabama.

194
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:03,000
You entered the sanitarium because to break losses in...

195
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,000
Was it early 60s?

196
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:07,000
63 January.

197
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And we're there until March of 64.

198
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:13,000
So a year and a couple of months.

199
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:16,000
And I know that having read some of the things you've written...

200
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:17,000
...that were that experience.

201
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:20,000
It was difficult, including reasons obviously related to race.

202
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:25,000
Can you describe the essence of your experience in those months?

203
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:31,000
Well, I love the impatience.

204
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:36,000
It was a segregated facility.

205
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:38,000
You had to enter. I did.

206
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:40,000
The back door.

207
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:42,000
Up some steps.

208
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
I can still remember at age 68...

209
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:48,000
...the... the...

210
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
...bannisters or whatever you call them, rickety.

211
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:53,000
I was extremely weak.

212
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:00,000
I came up in an ambulance from Tuskegee, John Andrew Memorial Hospital.

213
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:03,000
I knew about the tuberculosis.

214
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,000
It was a plague.

215
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:09,000
And then being in the...

216
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
...at John Andrews...

217
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:16,000
...in the isolation unit.

218
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:18,000
I had oxygen at that time.

219
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:19,000
I had a tin.

220
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:21,000
You never looked at it.

221
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:24,000
And everybody was in white.

222
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:28,000
All covered up, masked, head, dough.

223
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:32,000
So I knew this was something very drastic.

224
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:35,000
Because I really didn't know about TB and consumption.

225
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:41,000
I knew about cancer, which was called a dreaded big C.

226
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:44,000
But I did not really know about burgloses.

227
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:48,000
I didn't even know it affected the lungs.

228
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:55,000
So I'm already traumatized by this disease.

229
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:59,000
So when I get up to Lafayette, Alabama, I mean Lafayette, Alabama.

230
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:06,000
And it's Benson, I believe it is, I have the correct name, sanatorium.

231
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:09,000
The front of the building is very impressive.

232
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:15,000
I have a photo of the building here in my archives at home.

233
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:18,000
Very impressive.

234
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:23,000
Now, mind you, I have not been around white people.

235
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,000
And those few I was around were not authority figures.

236
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:37,000
So we ride on around, go through the back, gravel and red dirt.

237
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:42,000
As I say down south, you know the red dirt.

238
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:50,000
And the ambulance people helped me out a week, week, week.

239
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:57,000
So I go through this back door, which is a vestibule,

240
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:02,000
but it served as an intake room.

241
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:05,000
I knew something then was wrong.

242
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:10,000
So after the intake and all the paperwork, there's this vestibule.

243
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:19,000
And the vestibule leads to a horizontal perpendicular hallway.

244
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:22,000
Coming in, I go to the left.

245
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:28,000
There are patients in the hall on beds.

246
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:32,000
There are three rooms.

247
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:39,000
The first room in which I was placed had three beds.

248
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:46,000
The second huge room, I think might have had six to eight beds.

249
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:53,000
You cross that hall and there was a little black and white TV

250
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:00,000
that was smaller than the television that I ever had in any of my homes or boats.

251
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:09,000
And then across the hall was another huge room with about eight to ten patients.

252
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:12,000
You're describing the segregated black section of the room.

253
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:18,000
And that's the woman's side.

254
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:26,000
The bathroom was, let me if I can describe you,

255
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:36,000
you got the vestibule, then you come up to this horizontal hallway perpendicular.

256
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,000
And then after you pass that entrance to the hallway,

257
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:46,000
there is another hallway that continues vertically.

258
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:48,000
And it's massive.

259
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:50,000
At least it looks massive to me.

260
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:53,000
And glistening the floors.

261
00:26:53,000 --> 00:27:00,000
And on that side, you had the kitchen.

262
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:05,000
And then you had the bathroom on the other side.

263
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:08,000
If I'm making sense across the hallway.

264
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:18,000
I did not know that men were on the other side of the hallway from the women's section.

265
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:21,000
So they placed me in the three-bedroom.

266
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,000
I guess that was for the elite.

267
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
And of course it was crowded.

268
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:34,000
And I guess for the first six months,

269
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:42,000
which shots every day, it's struck my son, and trying to get strength.

270
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:47,000
I didn't really pay any attention to the overall conditions,

271
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:53,000
except that I knew when I was able to get up and walk and go to the various huge wards,

272
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:54,000
I guess.

273
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:55,000
I was in the private room.

274
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,000
The two wards, I found it horrifying.

275
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:01,000
And we were clean up.

276
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:04,000
And I thought that was part of the therapy,

277
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:08,000
because I now know it's a lung problem, and I need to be strengthened.

278
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:13,000
And we were clean up our area, mop, and everything.

279
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:19,000
And I thought it was part of the therapy of strengthening oneself.

280
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:24,000
And so here it is now about June.

281
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:29,000
I'm strong, or.

282
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:34,000
And a little girl comes in with her mommy,

283
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:40,000
and they're in the ward, the big, the larger ward.

284
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:48,000
And I feel a responsibility to be her mentor.

285
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:52,000
I had learned how to crochet, and I had already known how to crochet,

286
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:54,000
but I crocheted so much.

287
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:59,000
I had it made lace, and you know, I was, you know, all of that.

288
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:06,000
Coming from my learning from my grandmother, on my mama's side, mommy.

289
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:12,000
So I asked to be moved to the larger ward,

290
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:14,000
so I could be with the little girl.

291
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:17,000
Her mama was very deathly ill.

292
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:23,000
Never, ever got from under the oxygen tent.

293
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:25,000
And I guess it's about August.

294
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:31,000
Well, before, no, it's August now.

295
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:33,000
Yes, August.

296
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,000
And there's the March on Washington.

297
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:40,000
And we sit on this little bitty, black and white TV.

298
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,000
And of course, at that time, the state,

299
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:47,000
Governor Wallace, I think, was governor.

300
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:51,000
And the state could just take away the television.

301
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:54,000
It was just going what we call it the blink.

302
00:29:54,000 --> 00:30:00,000
But I saw another bit to discern that this was important.

303
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:05,000
This was about black people, it was about our rights, it was about freedom.

304
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:11,000
And then soon after that, in September, the four little girls in Birmingham.

305
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:15,000
And that came on, because we all watched the news, these hour in CIS,

306
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
because you had to fight about what we were going to look at.

307
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:21,000
A lot of them watched the little, when it searched for the moral,

308
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:23,000
whatever those little soapbox.

309
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:28,000
But the news came on at 6 o'clock, so there was not a conflict.

310
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:31,000
And I always wanted to watch the news.

311
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And so I then learned, I saw my goodness.

312
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:36,000
Wow.

313
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:40,000
So then I took an extremely special interest.

314
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:43,000
And the little girl, she was nine years old.

315
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And for the life of me, I cannot remember her name.

316
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
And by the way, we very seldom knew our last names.

317
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:58,000
And it was at that point that I said, look, the movement is wherever you are.

318
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:00,000
I have been taught that.

319
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
That the movement is not something that's imposed.

320
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:07,000
It's not an extracurricular activity.

321
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:09,000
It's wherever you are.

322
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:11,000
That's sanitarium.

323
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:17,000
Sanitarium became my movement base.

324
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:24,000
And I said, now we need to, meanwhile, they were bringing magazines to us on the card in that business.

325
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:30,000
And so my mind said, one of this place has a library.

326
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:34,000
And I asked, I say, is there a librarian here?

327
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:37,000
And they did, I think there was stunned.

328
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:44,000
And out of that, oh yes, I don't know what the motivation was.

329
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:49,000
And I said, it's probably up there, shiny hall.

330
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And so one day I took the little girl by hand.

331
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:58,000
And I ventured.

332
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:03,000
And there were maintenance people, housekeeping people,

333
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:07,000
mopping and sweeping and taking care of them.

334
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:09,000
But we had to clean up our own.

335
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:13,000
There was a game room.

336
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:19,000
You know, it was, what do you call splendor?

337
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:23,000
There was a baby grand piano.

338
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:26,000
And what we would call a sitting room warplowler.

339
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:31,000
And I had taken music lessons all of my life.

340
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:33,000
And I went there.

341
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:38,000
And I sat down and I started playing, bomb, bomb, bomb, show pen, C sharp, pray,

342
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:40,000
Louder, C sharp, minor.

343
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:47,000
And you know, it has a real classic, classic kind of, dumb, dumb, and all.

344
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:52,000
And of course, the white people were just stunned, if not angry.

345
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:57,000
And across from the sitting room, there was a sitting room that was the front entrance.

346
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And it's best to be able to, and then on the other side of that was the library.

347
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:09,000
And I went over there after, after white people started looking at me peculiar,

348
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:12,000
my little brain said, oh no, you're not going to do this.

349
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:15,000
Because there I have you up here like a toy.

350
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:21,000
And I'll become up here playing, you know, which made me fundamentally no different

351
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:22,000
than a manny.

352
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:27,000
I didn't care about a white child at the expense of my own.

353
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:29,000
So I said, but it stopped this.

354
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:33,000
So I go to the library and I pull out some books.

355
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:37,000
And then I politely walk back down the hall.

356
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:41,000
Nobody said anything to me.

357
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,000
The doctor was in and out, so he was like not a real participant.

358
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:51,000
And I guess this was a head nurse or whoever was in charge, but she was a woman.

359
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:56,000
And she came to talk to me quietly that I was not to do that.

360
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:02,000
So I go on up to the library, white woman, and all over a white star.

361
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:09,000
Kind of remind me later on the nurse that threw over the Cuckoo's Nest.

362
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:16,000
And I told her that I'm a college student, and this is a little girl.

363
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:20,000
And you all need to work out some kind of arrangement.

364
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:25,000
For me and this child to go to the library.

365
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:30,000
And I guess there was a human inkling in her.

366
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:37,000
And so she arranged, once Jim Crow terms, for me and the little girl to go to the library.

367
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:42,000
I can't remember what day's, but we would go and nobody would be in there but us.

368
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:49,000
And we could look and pull the books and maybe stay for about 30 minutes and read the books

369
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:52,000
because we couldn't bring them back.

370
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:56,000
We could bring magazines for not the books and sit up there and read the books.

371
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
I read their children's stories or whatever.

372
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:08,000
And so that was my first, not my first protest, but that was, and then secondly I got tired of the food.

373
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:11,000
They always gave us boiler food.

374
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:18,000
And what I mean by boiler food, greens, which were healthy, I'm not opposed to that.

375
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:23,000
But boiler food, potatoes, stew.

376
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:29,000
And I asked one day, I said, how come we eat all of this kind of food?

377
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:32,000
Don't y'all have some other kinds of food?

378
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:36,000
And whatever the whoever this nurse was.

379
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:40,000
She said, well, Gwen, you probably won't like this food.

380
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:42,000
That's what what is it?

381
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:45,000
She said, well, we're having oysters stew.

382
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:50,000
I said, mate, what cream or milk.

383
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:53,000
And she said, oh you, I see us, man.

384
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,000
I was polite.

385
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:00,000
I said, oh, I like to see the menu.

386
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:06,000
And I think we ought to have a chance to look at the menu and see what you're all serving, totally.

387
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:09,000
And put it on our little Bolton boy.

388
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:11,000
And after that, she didn't say anything, still.

389
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:12,000
And they didn't know what to do.

390
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:14,000
They were ready to hurry on and get me out of there.

391
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:17,000
And then I decided I'd go to the kitchen.

392
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:21,000
Because see, when you walked down the little colored section,

393
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:28,000
and to the main expanse of hallway, the kitchen was right there, not too far away.

394
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:31,000
And I went in the kitchen and looked.

395
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:36,000
And by that time, I guess I had a reputation because nobody had monitoring me,

396
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:40,000
nobody threatened me, nobody insulted me.

397
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:43,000
They were polite.

398
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:51,000
And I looked and looked and looked and saw what they saw, and then they started posting the menu.

399
00:36:51,000 --> 00:37:02,000
So when they had perched fish as opposed to whitey, when they had big fish instead of fried fish,

400
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:12,000
I would choose, you know, other, and try to encourage my fellow patients to do likewise.

401
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:16,000
Now the other thing that was interesting about Benson Sanatorium,

402
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:25,000
they had a chapel, you know, a little prayer kind of room on the listening hallway.

403
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:28,000
We had to go outdoors.

404
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:34,000
And we would go outdoors and sit at this wooden table under a tree.

405
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:37,000
I think it was a pecan tree.

406
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:39,000
And that's where we had our services.

407
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:42,000
We never had a minister.

408
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:44,000
We would conduct our own services.

409
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:48,000
And the songs were always one I remember most.

410
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:52,000
Way over yonder where Jesus is.

411
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:55,000
Way over yonder where Jesus is.

412
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:02,000
I got a mother over yonder where I remember that of course my mother had passed.

413
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:11,000
And I learned a whole lot of new songs that we never signed in the Baptist churches here in Montgomery.

414
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:19,000
They were real, I used to call it, Dirtges of Christian music.

415
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:24,000
They were sad.

416
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:28,000
And they were always about death.

417
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:31,000
So it was at an impact on me.

418
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:33,000
Let me ask about all this.

419
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:37,000
Obviously we're polite.

420
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:43,000
And though youthful, a young adult obviously had an era of confidence and assertion about yourself.

421
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:48,000
Why do you think they tolerated you in those demands that you made?

422
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:51,000
Given what they might have said.

423
00:38:51,000 --> 00:39:05,000
I think that they were impressed with my intelligence.

424
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:14,000
I think that they had made the assumption that black people were ignorant and stupid.

425
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:20,000
And when they could see that I would discuss with them.

426
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:22,000
I was determined.

427
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:25,000
I was not trying to raise them.

428
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:27,000
You were left there consciousness.

429
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:28,000
No, that was not.

430
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:32,000
You know, but I would say things.

431
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:43,000
Why is it important for you to keep black people and little children from learning?

432
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:49,000
And I think they had no answers or couldn't answer.

433
00:39:49,000 --> 00:39:52,000
And they knew I was going to be temporary.

434
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:57,000
So they were really figuring out how to get me out of there.

435
00:39:57,000 --> 00:39:59,000
And would tolerate me.

436
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:04,000
And I think to a certain extent respect me at the same time.

437
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:11,000
Because I made dollies and stuffed stuff.

438
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:13,000
Stuff, what do you call ducks?

439
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:16,000
I can't, you know, little stuffed animals.

440
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:19,000
And then my folks were sending me pajamas.

441
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:24,000
You say I also have that extended support base.

442
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:27,000
I'm sure they had read about me, my grandparents.

443
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:31,000
And all they knew also that if something happened to me wrong,

444
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:37,000
there will be at least some level of hell to play, or to pay.

445
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:40,000
And whenever they were visiting times, my folks came.

446
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:42,000
Tuskegee people came.

447
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:47,000
So I think it's that support base as well.

448
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:51,000
And I would make ducks and give them to them.

449
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,000
You know, the little head nurse who would come in all the time.

450
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:57,000
I gave her a little duck.

451
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:03,000
I used to make these hard crochet hearts.

452
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:07,000
You know, I knew out of stitch and double stitch and pick up stitch.

453
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:12,000
And then stuff, you know, get satin and then stuff with cotton.

454
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:14,000
And I would make little ones.

455
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:20,000
And I would give them to the doctors and people like that.

456
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:22,000
Thank you for that description.

457
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:25,000
And by the way, I was only going to want to call it a education.

458
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:30,000
Well, with some, because I had not graduated.

459
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:34,000
Sure, let's call it a campus.

460
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:35,000
That's lovely.

461
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:36,000
We're rolling again.

462
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:38,000
We're back after a short break.

463
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:46,000
Dr. Patton, let me ask you about arriving back on the Tuskegee campus in the fall of 64.

464
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:51,000
It's a campus now that SNCC folks are visiting everywhere.

465
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:54,000
Pick up the story with what you came back to.

466
00:41:54,000 --> 00:42:01,000
Well, when I came back, I had a roommate.

467
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:04,000
Cannot think of her name.

468
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:08,000
But tuberculosis was considered like a plague.

469
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:11,000
And she did not want to be my roommate.

470
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:12,000
She was scared to death.

471
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:16,000
I was one big, fat disease.

472
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,000
And that bothered me to some extent.

473
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:23,000
But it didn't because the community among government

474
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:24,000
embraced me.

475
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:30,000
I got a job in the cleaners between, you know, Carvalesci.

476
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:32,000
And I had a sense of humor.

477
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:34,000
My folks loved me.

478
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:39,000
They will make it their business to drink a glass of water.

479
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:45,000
From my glass of water, you know, they didn't put any disinfectant in the water.

480
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:49,000
And so I had to go always have this background story.

481
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:52,000
So one day I met, I'm still wearing my...

482
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:59,000
I was saying with mommy, but I met my cousin, Flora, and Aunt Jix, the Lottie Dot Teachers.

483
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:04,000
And I'm eating there.

484
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:06,000
And I'm watching dishes.

485
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:10,000
And I poured some chlorox in the water.

486
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:15,000
And they said, when you don't have to do that, you know, being very, what do you call?

487
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:18,000
Someone paternalistic and caring and loving.

488
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:20,000
I said, yes, I do.

489
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:22,000
And they said, no, no, we love you.

490
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:23,000
That's okay.

491
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:25,000
I said, I don't need to catch a cold from one of y'all.

492
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:26,000
I might get to be again.

493
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:27,000
And they all laugh.

494
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:32,000
So I kind of, you know, so I was prepared.

495
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:41,000
But when this roommate acted such a fool and trying to make me into a big fat germ, I asked

496
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:44,000
for her to leave or to put me somewhere else.

497
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:49,000
And so the school I was in Travis Hall, which was the honor dorm.

498
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:52,000
So the school moved her.

499
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:55,000
So I was at my own room.

500
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:56,000
You see?

501
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:58,000
So I was really privileged.

502
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Everybody else had a roommate, but me.

503
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:06,000
So when the SNCC people would come, the women, they could all stay in my room.

504
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:07,000
And they did.

505
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:10,000
And they all knew I'd had to be.

506
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:13,000
And they never made an issue out of it.

507
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:16,000
You know, whatever cake my grandma sent, they ate it.

508
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:17,000
And they did all for it.

509
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:18,000
But they bit it all.

510
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:24,000
So was that sisterhood that gave me even further strength from the greater community?

511
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:25,000
How did you make of these?

512
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:26,000
Let me ask.

513
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:27,000
What did you make of these SNCC women?

514
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:28,000
They were tough.

515
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:36,000
They were tough.

516
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:38,000
Committed.

517
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:39,000
Resolute.

518
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:40,000
Resolute.

519
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:43,000
But sometimes.

520
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:50,000
Sometimes.

521
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:56,000
I thought that sometimes I thought maybe I was too deep.

522
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:01,000
You know that maybe there was something wrong with the way I was thinking.

523
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:08,000
Because I was never for integration ever in my life.

524
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:09,000
What were your points then?

525
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:16,000
These segregation, equal opportunity, fairness, justice.

526
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And see that goes all the way back to when I was in high school, I graduated from high school

527
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:24,000
in Montgomery.

528
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:30,000
And they wanted me to go to University of Alabama because I had the school authorities,

529
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:35,000
the principal, and my history teacher, my government teacher.

530
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:42,000
Because I had, because I was up, no, from up north.

531
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:46,000
But I'm in a black community up there.

532
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:47,000
But they don't see that.

533
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:53,000
They saw that I was from, even though they don't even know about Inxter, but Detroit.

534
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:56,000
So they made these assumptions.

535
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:04,000
And so they assumed that I would know how to interact with white people and not be frightened

536
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:08,000
or afraid of what I would not have been.

537
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:13,000
But I would see the sense of what going to University of Alabama for what?

538
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:17,000
How has University of Alabama distinguished itself?

539
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:22,000
You know all my life I've learned about George Washington, Carver, Booker T. Washington,

540
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:25,000
Yams (sweet potatoes) and peanuts, and peanuts, and science.

541
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:28,000
You know what?

542
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:35,000
So when they said, well, there's football and beer, Brian.

543
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:38,000
I said, oh, can I be a cheerleader?

544
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:40,000
And they just considered that frivolous.

545
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:43,000
And I wanted to be the world's best cheerleader.

546
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:48,000
I mean, that was like an avocation of mine before I was in this mysterious car accident.

547
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:51,000
So they said, don't be frivolous, Gwen, don't be silly.

548
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:55,000
So when they said that, I said, well, I'm not going up there.

549
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:02,000
So getting back, if I can make the story a whole, I was never for integration, for the sake of integration.

550
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:05,000
And then you have to also understand my upbringing.

551
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:10,000
You know, I didn't think I learned any better sitting next to a white child.

552
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:13,000
You know, that was not my paradigm.

553
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:18,000
I didn't define myself in juxtaposition to white people.

554
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:25,000
And that was reinforced with my grandmother, which goes all the way back to 56 on the bus boycott.

555
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:28,000
I mean, on the bus after the boycott.

556
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:31,000
And she always sat in the back.

557
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:34,000
And I will always sit up in the front and aggravate white folks.

558
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:38,000
They was an ensquirming and pushing and all, being a kid.

559
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:41,000
I'm 14, not back at the time, 15.

560
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:43,000
And one day there were no white folks in the bus.

561
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:45,000
So I went and sat in the back with mommy.

562
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:49,000
I said, we walked all these days, you walked.

563
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:54,000
And mommy and daddy sent money and shoes and did what I had to do.

564
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:56,000
And you still sit in the back.

565
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:01,000
I thought she was capitulating.

566
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:04,000
That she, I knew she was a block captain.

567
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:06,000
I knew she was in the movement.

568
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:09,000
I knew she thought voting was important.

569
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:14,000
But I still thought maybe you are afraid of white folks in a certain kind of way.

570
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:18,000
And she very lady like extremely lady like,

571
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:24,000
whoo, had far more class than my la la da teacher relatives.

572
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:29,000
And she always called me Gwendolyn, the whole name, not Gwen, but Gwendolyn.

573
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:31,000
Very proper.

574
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:39,000
And she said, Gwendolyn, the bus boycott was not about sitting next to white people.

575
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:43,000
It was about sitting anywhere you please.

576
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:46,000
And I am pleased to sit here.

577
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:50,000
And I had to sit back and take that in.

578
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:55,000
Which altered my whole thought process.

579
00:48:55,000 --> 00:49:04,000
So when I meet SNCC people, all men and women in 64, this is before black power.

580
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:08,000
And they were about to sit here.

581
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:11,000
And they were about integrating and doesn't so.

582
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,000
I had a different kind of perspective.

583
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:17,000
But I knew these were some good people.

584
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:19,000
They were dedicated.

585
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:25,000
And maybe I need to look at my perspective as well to understand be self-critical.

586
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:27,000
But did not alter.

587
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:30,000
Because the more I saw, the more I said this is silly.

588
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:36,000
And it began with the desegregation of schools in Macon County.

589
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:42,000
And they were getting the middle class kids, the professional children,

590
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:47,000
to integrate the white school, which was downtown Tuskegee.

591
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:52,000
When the poor black and the poor working folks lived in downtown Tuskegee.

592
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:57,000
So they could have what, walking distances to the white folks homes,

593
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:03,000
to clean up, take you at a chilling, and those ones to be the yard man or the handy man.

594
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:08,000
So while we're going way over here in a bourgeois subdivision,

595
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:14,000
which is going to require busing, when we got black chillin right over here.

596
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:18,000
So that was my first, oh no, it ain't about integration.

597
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:19,000
You know, these folks.

598
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And then at Tuskegee, you had the Negro swimming pool,

599
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:29,000
where the professional, and so, you know, chilling,

600
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:33,000
and the BA in Tuskegee Institute, chilling.

601
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:36,000
And I use that word purposely.

602
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:40,000
Swammed in the Negro pool, let's say on a Monday and the Wednesday.

603
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:47,000
And the poor and the working class Negro children swammed on the same pool on a two-cent Thursday.

604
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:54,000
So I saw right away the class problem in the cast.

605
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:01,000
And I had to just really struggle with this thing integration,

606
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:05,000
an integration for home.

607
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:09,000
And so I just had a different perspective.

608
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:14,000
Let me ask about some of these very thoughts that are right at the front of your mind,

609
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:20,000
I imagine, when you are sorting out what SNCC, the creation on campus of TIAL.

610
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:21,000
Right.

611
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:22,000
In early 65.

612
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:26,000
Yeah, I didn't believe in submerging.

613
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:28,000
And see, that goes all the way back.

614
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:33,000
Yeah, describe that didn't believe in submerging with a walk in your explainer.

615
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:42,000
You should not take the identity of a grassroots organization.

616
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:47,000
You should not subsune them.

617
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:54,000
As an organizer, you should do everything to lift them up so they can have their own identity,

618
00:51:54,000 --> 00:52:02,000
their own structure, their own sense of how they are going to run that community organization.

619
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:08,000
Now that didn't come to me as a brilliant thought.

620
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:13,000
That came to me as a result of MIA.

621
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:20,000
When the Southern Christian Leadership Conference formed in 1957, at my church,

622
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:28,000
I talk southern touch with HHS, a HHS missionary Baptist Church.

623
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:35,000
And they wanted the MIA to become a chapter, an SCLC chapter,

624
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:45,000
and my grandparents and the folks whom I respected at work as a child and as a teenager said,

625
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:54,000
no, it was a Montgomery Improvement Association that spearheaded and directed and kept together

626
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:57,000
the 381 days we walked.

627
00:52:57,000 --> 00:53:01,000
We are not going to give up that identity.

628
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:08,000
And to this very day, we have never had an SCLC chapter, but we still have MIA.

629
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:13,000
So I'm coming from that experience and bringing it to SNCC.

630
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:16,000
Now we have an organization.

631
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:20,000
It's called a Tuskegee Institute Advancement League, TIAL.

632
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:23,000
We were here before you got here.

633
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:28,000
We were involved in direct action, action, chair.

634
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:30,000
You know, we got a movement.

635
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:36,000
We're not only fighting the race question, we're fighting the class question within Black people,

636
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:43,000
which they had not a clue, because they subsumed all Black folks were alike.

637
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:47,000
And we saw the sharp distinctions.

638
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:56,000
Dr. Foster, who was President of Tuskegee, can I have him on a video by the way?

639
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:59,000
In the archives.

640
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:01,000
What have a Christmas party?

641
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:05,000
See, at Tuskegee was really a very bourgeois school.

642
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:06,000
We didn't watch.

643
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:08,000
We had a laundry on campus.

644
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:17,000
And they would come and collect our clothing and our linen and wash it and bring it back.

645
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:23,000
I mean, it was a very bourgy school as close to a prep school as you could get.

646
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:30,000
But Dr. Foster, the President, would have the laundry people, the maintenance people,

647
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:37,000
the help on the grounds, not the grounds superintendent.

648
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:39,000
He was in the bourgy class.

649
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:46,000
And one Christmas party, and then the professional and the VA people, had another Christmas party.

650
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:51,000
So when I became a student by the President, which I'm leaping,

651
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:56,000
I would always talk to him about cost effectiveness.

652
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:02,000
And that became a principle of mine as we interacted and we became very close.

653
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:11,000
I said, you know, it cost more money for you to have two distinct Christmas parties than if you had one.

654
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:18,000
And he being a businessman, you know, with a PhD, probably a master's in business.

655
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:23,000
And I don't know what his PhDs was at because I don't know if they had PhD in businesses at the time.

656
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:26,000
He could look at the bottom line.

657
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:28,000
And he began to reason with me.

658
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:32,000
And soon afterwards, we'd be almost became peers.

659
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:35,000
But I respected him as an authority.

660
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:38,000
And plus, he had impeccable grammar.

661
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:42,000
In fact, all of the black presidents, not all of them, many,

662
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:49,000
were sitting there, writing speeches to him, to prove read and edit and all that.

663
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:53,000
And I was impressed, you know, with his grammar.

664
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:58,000
There's so much activity on the campus in the fall of 64, in early 65.

665
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:05,000
But let me take the story to March, March 65.

666
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:10,000
Your election as president will follow,

667
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:17,000
but you are a very significant figure in organizing inside TIAL and campus figure.

668
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:25,000
Can you tell the story of those several weeks in March from Bloody Sunday through the Alabama State Capitol?

669
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:30,000
Well, you'll see the Alabama State Capitol a couple of times because...

670
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:33,000
Yeah, the March that didn't turn around.

671
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:36,000
Tuskegee had become a liberated zone.

672
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:39,000
I wish you knew how to get the old.

673
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:41,000
Snicks they were, they wanted to.

674
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:43,000
They went to classes.

675
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:46,000
They ate in the dining hall.

676
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,000
You know, the whole nine yards.

677
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:51,000
So that is to say that the administration had given up and had to...

678
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:53,000
Totally given up.

679
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:57,000
And we had faculty support.

680
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:04,000
Gene Wiley, Maggie McGee, Dean Wassertrom.

681
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:15,000
It was a very complex situation because Dr. Foster had hired all of these white people

682
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:27,000
who were progressive, which always fascinated me because most white people who come to black college campuses are progressives.

683
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:32,000
You know, and Gene Wiley was black.

684
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:39,000
And so they displace the black professionals.

685
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:44,000
I never forget the slide of meeting, little on as when I was doing my president.

686
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:50,000
A black and white professor is getting together to see if we can work this thing through.

687
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:55,000
Because the black professors were becoming nationalist.

688
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:00,000
You know, and the white professors were our buddies.

689
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:03,000
So anyway, that is another story.

690
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:15,000
But prior to the march from Selma to Montgomery.

691
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:18,000
SNCC, as I said, was everywhere on campus.

692
00:58:18,000 --> 00:58:21,000
And had freedom.

693
00:58:21,000 --> 00:58:28,000
And Dr. Foster really not knowing what to do.

694
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:34,000
And Tuskegee being a quasi-private and public institution.

695
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:37,000
The state had no authority.

696
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:42,000
You know, Governor Wallace and the state apparatus.

697
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:52,000
So students would go to Lowndes County, go to Dallas County, you know, and help organize.

698
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:59,000
And that made sense to us because we were now toying with the whole concept that education has to be relevant.

699
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:06,000
And if you're not serving the community, then what good does it mean for you to get a degree?

700
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:12,000
And so we were win those arguments intellectually.

701
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:15,000
And we played excellent chess.

702
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:19,000
I was a real excellent bridge player.

703
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:26,000
You know, so it was all of that if you can see the complexity of what we were becoming.

704
00:59:26,000 --> 00:59:29,000
Plus our professors had us read.

705
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:31,000
They took Phil.

706
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:34,000
When you read that, I mean, I was supposed to come out of that.

707
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:39,000
You know, and then we had Negro history was compulsory.

708
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:47,000
You know, so when you read W.E.B. Du Bois, whatever his limitations, or Book of Tea, whatever his limit,

709
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:50,000
how do you suppose to come out of that?

710
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:54,000
I mean, I thought education was to inform you and change your behavior.

711
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:58,000
And so it changed our behavior to be more revolutionary.

712
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:03,000
You know, I dealt with the whole question of homosexuality.

713
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:08,000
In fact, my sophomore paper was on homosexuality.

714
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:12,000
I want to look that up in the card catalog at the time.

715
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:16,000
And I always said, deviant behavior.

716
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:28,000
And I had a cousin, Bobby, who lived with me while I was in Inkster, at Wayne State University Library Science,

717
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:37,000
who was in love with a neighborhood family, a friend, that my brother and I knew was Sissy.

718
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:39,000
Because that's what we called him, a Sissy.

719
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:41,000
His name was Junior's name was Robert Harris.

720
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:44,000
They both died so I can call him name.

721
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:47,000
And we love Junior. We call him Junior.

722
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:49,000
And we loved him.

723
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:52,000
But we could not understand what Bobby didn't see.

724
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:56,000
That he was a Sissy. We didn't know Gaye was not a term.

725
01:00:56,000 --> 01:00:58,000
And anyhow, she got pregnant.

726
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:01,000
So we said, well, maybe he ain't.

727
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:03,000
Right? You know.

728
01:01:03,000 --> 01:01:05,000
And they had a son.

729
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:08,000
And they got married.

730
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:12,000
So I'm still close to Junior.

731
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:17,000
And he looked at me and said, one day, are you homosexual?

732
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:20,000
And he looked at me and he admitted it.

733
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:22,000
So that's why I want to write a paper on this.

734
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:27,000
I said, because when I look in the card catalog, all I see is deviant behavior.

735
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:29,000
And you ain't deviant to me.

736
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:31,000
You're a lot of fun.

737
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:32,000
I love you.

738
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:33,000
You know, so tell me.

739
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:37,000
That's what he told me about the Mattachine Press and San Francisco.

740
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:40,000
That's what he told me about a book.

741
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:45,000
I think with Twilight, I can't recall.

742
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:52,000
It was almost like a Bible to the gay world, male gay.

743
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:55,000
Twilight or something.

744
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:58,000
It has something to do with stars.

745
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:04,000
And he told me what to read and Mattachine Press and San Francisco and all of that business.

746
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:07,000
So I'm open to that now.

747
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:11,000
I'm not quite open up to Lesbian just yet,

748
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:16,000
and we call them Dykes then, Bull Divers or Dykes.

749
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:20,000
But I was open up to homosexuality.

750
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:22,000
And that's what I learned when I read about it.

751
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:24,000
That's what I learned about Lesbos.

752
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:25,000
I never forget that.

753
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:27,000
And then I learned the clinical term.

754
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:31,000
If you will, I should use the word clinical.

755
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:33,000
I should use that term at all.

756
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:35,000
Lesbos, Lesbian.

757
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:38,000
So I began to lose people through that.

758
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:47,000
So I don't know how I got to this, but coming to SNCC.

759
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:51,000
I don't know if there were so much in the heat of the day

760
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:56,000
that they didn't do a lot of thinking or contemplation like I did.

761
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:02,000
And maybe others, that they were quite there.

762
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:06,000
Okay, that's back to the record.

763
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:09,000
I'm sorry, I have to be careful.

764
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:14,000
I say this.

765
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:20,000
So in TIAL, we had these kinds of discussions

766
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:26,000
about people, personalities, identities, lifestyle.

767
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:29,000
George Ware, who was from Buffalo, New York.

768
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:34,000
George Davis, Rhode Island.

769
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:40,000
Sammy Younge Jr, who had gone to school, up in New Hampshire and over.

770
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:42,000
No, he didn't go to the end of it.

771
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:44,000
We went to one of those prep schools.

772
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:46,000
These are enrolled students at Tuskegee Bridge.

773
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:47,000
Yeah, enrolled.

774
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:49,000
My classmates, my peers.

775
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:53,000
The girls were Ruby Taylor, who was basically,

776
01:03:53,000 --> 01:03:56,000
she was from the Black Belt here in Alabama, Pickens.

777
01:03:57,000 --> 01:04:00,000
County.

778
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:07,000
Other girls, Kathleen Neal Cleaver, was in and out.

779
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:09,000
She had been to a prep school.

780
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:19,000
In other words, there was a broader, what do you call, perspective.

781
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:23,000
And different levels on the spectrum of understanding.

782
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:28,000
And we could have those discussions within TIAL.

783
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:32,000
Snip was so caught up in the heat of the day

784
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:37,000
that we very seldom had philosophical discussions at that time.

785
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:38,000
We're talking.

786
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:40,000
You're much more tactical.

787
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:42,000
How to deal with SLC.

788
01:04:42,000 --> 01:04:47,000
You know, you're serving grassroots organizing, day in, day out, drudgery.

789
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:50,000
You come home, you're tired.

790
01:04:50,000 --> 01:04:55,000
You've been beaten by a clubster or a sympathizer.

791
01:04:55,000 --> 01:04:59,000
And so you didn't have that luxury.

792
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:02,000
Even though SNCC did do a great deal of talking,

793
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:05,000
or as we would say, great deal of talking.

794
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:08,000
But it was all about, who are you?

795
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:11,000
Where do you come from?

796
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:14,000
And I don't know what that was about.

797
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:16,000
It was an integrated group.

798
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:21,000
It sounds like you're just about to crystallize that notion of the scholar activist.

799
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:23,000
Oh yeah, we had done that.

800
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:25,000
You know, you couldn't be dumb.

801
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:28,000
You know, you simply could not be dumb.

802
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:31,000
You cannot be in the struggle in the movement.

803
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:38,000
If you were not doing well in school, the movement could not have

804
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:41,000
been insolent.

805
01:05:41,000 --> 01:05:46,000
I had to use the word dumb, but that's, you know, the vernacular.

806
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:53,000
But undisciplined, unaware kinds of people.

807
01:05:53,000 --> 01:06:00,000
Didn't you have to once on that point answer, was it Stokely Carmichael?

808
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:02,000
Who put that question to you?

809
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:04,000
Is your education really valuable?

810
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:05,000
Oh yes.

811
01:06:05,000 --> 01:06:06,000
Oh yes.

812
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:13,000
Stokely, Stokely really tried to get all, because he was impressed with Tuskegee kids.

813
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:18,000
Plus we had also told the administration, this is what we're going to do.

814
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:23,000
You know, we are freedom fighters.

815
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:28,000
This institution has prepared us to be freedom fighters.

816
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:33,000
I mean, we were just not in arrogant terms, but in rational terms.

817
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:37,000
You know, what do you expect?

818
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:39,000
And Stokely was impressed with that.

819
01:06:39,000 --> 01:06:41,000
I'm sure they had that at Howard.

820
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:45,000
And it looked like they could have had that at Howard even better,

821
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:49,000
because they had a president who was already, they're a good march on all of that.

822
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:53,000
And perhaps they were intellects, but they dealt with it as an elitism thing.

823
01:06:53,000 --> 01:06:56,000
I know what Stokely [Carmichael] and [Mike] Thelwell and all of them were coming from.

824
01:06:56,000 --> 01:07:08,000
So, and they had also, Stoke people and Stoke men in particular,

825
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:15,000
had almost the same kind of attitude towards Southern blacks

826
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:23,000
as a variation of how those white folks saw me at Benson Sanatorium.

827
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:28,000
We were Southern, we were supposed to be country dance stereotypes, stereotypes,

828
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:34,000
not to be deep thinkers, let alone make analysis.

829
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:38,000
And I think that kind of set them back.

830
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:45,000
And Stokely wanted everybody to drop out and join SNCC.

831
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:50,000
And I confronted him, I say, you went back to Howard and got your degree.

832
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:53,000
How dare you do that?

833
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:56,000
Because also I saw a practical side.

834
01:07:56,000 --> 01:08:00,000
We needed the same reason that I had to tell Bettina Aptheker.

835
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:04,000
When she came down back in some years, I guess I was in 66,

836
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:07,000
prior to my break in my leg.

837
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:15,000
And she was astonished that we had an ROTC and we weren't picketing.

838
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:18,000
And I said, oh no, no, no, Bettina.

839
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:23,000
And I became very close and to her father and her mother.

840
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:25,000
I say these kids go to school.

841
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:34,000
Oh, I know it was. Bettina had come down and we had this grand parade of all these ROTC folk.

842
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:41,000
And General Chappy James was leading,

843
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:47,000
or General Benjamin O'Davis, because they both were Tuskegee Airmen and Tuskegee Grat.

844
01:08:47,000 --> 01:08:51,000
And Bettina was horrified.

845
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:55,000
And I said, no, no, no, Bettina.

846
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:01,000
I said, a lot of these students here need ROTC to get scholarships.

847
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:03,000
It's just that simple.

848
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:07,000
So it was a practical thing that Tuskegee kids had,

849
01:09:07,000 --> 01:09:10,000
as well as a philosophical underpinning.

850
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:13,000
And I don't think, stick people understood that very well,

851
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:16,000
nor did, and antiwar people later.

852
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:19,000
Because we had one of the best draft counseling centers.

853
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:23,000
You know, we knew how to do CO, conscientious objectors.

854
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:24,000
What are we going to get to that?

855
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:27,000
Okay. But getting back to Stokeley, Stokeley could not argue.

856
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:29,000
Even let me take you back.

857
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:34,000
Just for a calm new tongue, because I know that we're pressing against your day

858
01:09:34,000 --> 01:09:36,000
and when you need to leave this interview.

859
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:40,000
So let me have you talk about that March of 65.

860
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:44,000
From Bloody Sunday through you will go ultimately,

861
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:49,000
you'll go on Wednesday from buses from Tuskegee to Montgomery.

862
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:51,000
And then you will go and make the March also.

863
01:09:51,000 --> 01:09:52,000
Yes.

864
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:53,000
So tell me about that.

865
01:09:53,000 --> 01:09:54,000
Okay.

866
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:02,000
We're organizing for the March what's Nick people in Dallas County so forth.

867
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:07,000
I'm in meetings as direct action chair of TIAL,

868
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:13,000
with James Forman and others, Hosea Williams Williams, Dr. King and all,

869
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:17,000
and Birmingham at A.G. Gaston Motel.

870
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:23,000
And it was decided that we were going to leave kick off that Sunday.

871
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:27,000
And we were going to march till we got to Montgomery.

872
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:29,000
We thought it was going to be three days.

873
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:32,000
You know, we had no idea.

874
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:37,000
And that had been decided democratically.

875
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:40,000
So even though we were philosophical, we were practical,

876
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:42,000
we're also idealistic.

877
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:45,000
This is what we had decided.

878
01:10:45,000 --> 01:10:51,000
So we come back to Tuskegee and we're going to organize the East Black Belt.

879
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:52,000
East Black Belt.

880
01:10:52,000 --> 01:10:53,000
Okay.

881
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:56,000
Not only Tuskegee, Macon County, but also Bullock County,

882
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:01,000
which included Union Springs, which is a Black Belt County.

883
01:11:01,000 --> 01:11:07,000
And so Sammy takes the lead in that same young raising money and

884
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:12,000
stopping cars on what we call campus avenue, the main thoroughfare,

885
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:15,000
and to stop like collecting buckets of money,

886
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:18,000
ordering, see we were also very organized.

887
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:23,000
We were far more organized and SNCC by the way, in terms of logistics.

888
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:30,000
I was so concerned about the scholar activist concept that you could not cut classes

889
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:32,000
and go on a demonstration.

890
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:35,000
So we had to figure out who had cars, who had many cars,

891
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:40,000
but we had to figure that out and do a grid, you know, on matrix,

892
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:41,000
or whatever you would do.

893
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:46,000
And you would go and pick it downtown at the supermarket or the registrar's office.

894
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:51,000
We had transplanted every hour on the hour, so you would not miss a class.

895
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:01,000
SNCC was just, I mean, just like, what do you call startled, if you will.

896
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:09,000
But James Forman who is an organizer and a tactician, marveled at it.

897
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:19,000
And so he really became the mentor for tidal kids on campus.

898
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:22,000
So he was stokily soon left and went to Lowndes County,

899
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:24,000
because he can deal with the rule.

900
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:26,000
You understand the stereotype fit.

901
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:29,000
Oh, I don't know if I want this on the record or not.

902
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:33,000
But that's an assumption on my part.

903
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:42,000
And they were practical people, deep common sense, you know, self-taught,

904
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:46,000
were philosophical still are.

905
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:50,000
And their way of being philosophical, then we studied at.

906
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:52,000
I mean, they were going to go in deep thought.

907
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:58,000
They got all of the possibilities, you know, the obstacles and so forth.

908
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:02,000
And I think people will mantisize that.

909
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:07,000
But anyhow, form and became the key person at Tuskegee,

910
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:11,000
and stokily became the key person in Lowndes County,

911
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:14,000
for whatever reasons.

912
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:17,000
So blood is Sunday happened.

913
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:21,000
And we see it on television in the door,

914
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:24,000
because we were not there then.

915
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:29,000
And we were horrified like the rest of the nation and the world.

916
01:13:29,000 --> 01:13:33,000
So we really, we really, we really, we got a really gear up,

917
01:13:33,000 --> 01:13:37,000
get our stuff organized, organize the community, get cars.

918
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:41,000
You know, we go on the Montgomery, we go meet them.

919
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:45,000
And that, because we thought it was going to be Wednesday.

920
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:49,000
You have to remember three days we thought it take, three or four days.

921
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:57,000
And that Tuesday, I think it was Dr. King,

922
01:13:57,000 --> 01:14:05,000
Nellte, prayed and turned around.

923
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:11,000
Unprincipled, it had been agreed upon by the collective

924
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:14,000
that we were going to do this march.

925
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:18,000
Nyee, youngsters, how could he do that?

926
01:14:18,000 --> 01:14:23,000
He promised, I mean, we almost went into infantile, you know, behavior.

927
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:29,000
He promised, Nellte children, but you promised, how can you break your promise?

928
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:33,000
I mean, we were, then we became fortified.

929
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:35,000
But you were ranked.

930
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:39,000
Oh, I was mad as hell.

931
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:45,000
That night, Judge Frank M. Johnson Jr, they just put a big thing up there.

932
01:14:45,000 --> 01:14:50,000
And I give him credit because he did a lot of things subsequently, you know,

933
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:52,000
around mental health and jail and so forth.

934
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:54,000
His pen was a mighty sword.

935
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:58,000
Issued this injunction.

936
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:01,000
